Building a histogram

Imagine a histogram for the heights of a large group of women between the ages of 2020 and 4040.

  1. Answer the following questions about the histogram:

    1. What quantity should go on the xx-axis of the histogram?
    2. What quantity should go on the yy-axis of the histogram?
    Answer:
    1. The quantity on the xx-axis should be: .
    2. The quantity on the yy-axis should be: .
    2 attempts remaining
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    Reread the question. The yy-axis on a histogram always shows the number of data values (the frequency of values). The xx-axis always shows the values for the data themselves.

    STEP: Select the correct axis labels
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    This question is about making a histogram. Specifically, we need to figure out what quantities should go on the axes for a histogram about the situation in the question.

    The horizontal axis in a histogram must always show the possible values of the data. In this case the data values are the heights for the different women. So the xx-axis must show height.

    For any histogram the yy-axis always shows the number of data values in the various intervals. (This is often called the frequency.)

    For the histogram described in this question:

    1. The variable on the xx-axis should be: Height.
    2. The variable on the yy-axis should be: Number of women.
    Submit your answer as: and

    A

    B

    C

    D
    Answer:

    The most reasonable shape to expect is choice .

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Do you expect most of the heights to be in the middle of the values, or will they mostly be smaller values? Or will they be spread out equally for all the values?

    STEP: Think about the way the data values will be spread out
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    To answer this question, we need to think about how the data values for the heights will be spread out.

    The four images below show these basic situations:

    A

    Balanced shape: Most data values are in the centre with a balanced number of values on each side. This means values in the middle are more common than values on the left side or the right side. So a balanced distribution is more or less symmetric with the peak in the middle.

    B

    Flat shape: All data values are spread out equally. So values on the left side are just as common as values on the right side and in the middle. This typically represents something random. Note that a flat shape is not exactly flat - but it has no significant peaks.

    C

    Skewed right shape: The data values are clumped up on the left side with a "tail" to the right. This shows that for some reason the data values on the right side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are harder to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

    D

    Skewed left shape: The data values are clumped up on the right side with a "tail" to the left. This shows that for some reason the data values on the left side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are easier to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

    So which of these is the most reasonable to expect? The question is about the heights for a group of women. Some of these women will be a bit shorter than average and some will be taller. But most women will be a similar height in the middle. So the histogram should be balanced with a peak in the middle. That corresponds to the balanced shape.

    NOTE: It is possible that the histogram will have a different shape - we can't know for sure if we do not have the data values. So our answer is based on reasonable expectations about how tall women are.

    Therefore the most reasonable shape to expect is choice A.

Common histogram errors

The histogram below shows a data set about how many minutes 5555 different people spent crying after watching Titanic. But there is a problem: there is an error in the histogram.

What is the problem with this histogram? Select your answer from the choices below.

A The intervals should have equal widths
B The axis labels are swapped
C The x-axis values are incorrect
D There are not enough intervals
Answer:

The problem is choice .

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Compare the histogram to what you expect to see. What is different? What does not agree with the information given in the question?

STEP: Compare the given histogram to what you expect to see
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to identify the problem with the histogram given above. To do this we need to compare the histogram to what we expect to see.

The problem here is that the axis labels are wrong. A histogram should always have the number of data values in each interval (the frequency) on the vertical axis. The values of the data should be on the horizontal axis. But in this case they are switched.

The problem with the histogram is that the axis labels are swapped, which is choice B.

Common histogram errors

The histogram below shows a data set about how many minutes 6565 different people spent crying after watching Titanic. But there is a problem: there is an error in the histogram.

What is the problem with this histogram? Select your answer from the choices below.

A The intervals should have equal widths
B The axis labels are swapped
C The x-axis values are incorrect
D There are not enough intervals
Answer:

The problem is choice .

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Compare the histogram to what you expect to see. What is different? What does not agree with the information given in the question?

STEP: Compare the given histogram to what you expect to see
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to identify the problem with the histogram given above. To do this we need to compare the histogram to what we expect to see.

The purpose of a histogram is to show how grouped data are spread into various intervals. If there are not enough intervals then the histogram is not very useful. In this case there are only two intervals. Each interval is 1515 wide. This is not what we expect from a histogram: there are not enough intervals to show us a useful amount of detail for the data.

The problem with the histogram is that there are not enough intervals, which is choice D.

Histogram shapes

Suppose we have a data set for scores on a typical test in statistics. Which of the pictures below shows the shape we should expect for the histogram?

A

B

C

D
Answer:

The most reasonable shape to expect is choice .

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Do you expect most of the data values to be in the middle of the values, or will they mostly be smaller values? Or will they be spread out equally for all the values?

STEP: Think about the way the data values will be spread out
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

To answer this question, we need to think about how the data values for the results on the test will be spread out.

The images in the question show these four basic situations:

A

Balanced shape: Most data values are in the centre with a balanced number of values on each side. This means values in the middle are more common than values on the left side or the right side. So a balanced distribution is more or less symmetric with the peak in the middle.

B

Flat shape: All data values are spread out equally. So values on the left side are just as common as values on the right side and in the middle. This typically represents something random. Note that a flat shape is not exactly flat - but it has no significant peaks.

C

Skewed right shape: The data values are clumped up on the left side with a "tail" to the right. This shows that for some reason the data values on the right side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are harder to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

D

Skewed left shape: The data values are clumped up on the right side with a "tail" to the left. This shows that for some reason the data values on the left side are less common. This would happen if larger values (on the right side) are easier to achieve than smaller values (on the left side).

So which of these is the most reasonable to expect for the results on the test?

The data in this case are for a typical test. That probably means most results are pretty similar to each other. Results for students who are struggling will be lower, and students who know the material particularly well will have higher results. But results for a typical test are normally balanced.

NOTE: It is possible that the histogram will have a different shape - we can't know for sure if we do not have the data values. So our answer is based on reasonable expectations about the situation described in the question.

The most reasonable shape to expect is choice A.

Histograms vs bar graphs

  1. What is the difference between a histogram and a bar graph? Or are they the same?

    Pick your answer from the choices below.

    A Histograms show qualitative data while bar graphs do not.
    B Histograms show data with lines while bar graphs show data with bars.
    C Histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data.
    D There is no difference between a histogram and a bar graph.
    Answer:

    The correct description of the difference is option .

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Histograms are used for data which is grouped into intervals. Bar graphs show data which is organised into categories.

    STEP: Determine what types of data are appropriate for histograms and bar graphs
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    Histograms and bar graphs are easy to confuse because they look like each other. But they are not the same! The difference is the type of data that they show.

    • Histogram A histogram uses bars to show continuous data. The data must be grouped into intervals. The bars touch each other because the data are continuous. A histogram shows the same information as a frequency polygon, but with bars instead of a line.
    • Bar graph A bar graph uses bars to show categorical data. That means data which are organised into categories. For example, types of cars or different provinces are categories. Such data cannot be grouped in intervals because the categories are separate from each other. The bars often do not touch each other because the data are not continuous.

    One key difference between histograms and bar graphs is the order of the values on the horizontal axis. The values for a histogram must be in order, because the data are continuous. But for bar graphs the order of the values can change. They can change because the categories themselves do not have a specific order.

    TIP: To decide if data belong in a histogram or a bar graph, ask yourself if the order of the data groups can be shifted or not. If the order cannot be shifted, you are dealing with a histogram situation.

    The difference between histograms and bar graphs is that histograms show continuous quantitative data while bar graphs show categorical data. The correct choice is C.

The word cumulative means 'growing by adding one after the other'. The cumulative frequency of a class is the frequency for that class added to the frequency of all the previous classes. So, the cumulative frequency of the last class is equal to the whole sample size.

Group data is listed with non-overlapping interval classes such as a≤n<ba≤n<b (meaning nn is from aa up to but not including bb) or a<n≤ba<n≤b (meaning nn is from more than aa up to and including bb). The aa in these expressions represents the lower class boundary (telling you about the smallest value in the class) and the bb represents the upper class boundary (telling you about the biggest value in the class).

An ogive is an SS-shaped cumulative frequency graph. It is a line graph formed by plotting the cumulative frequency on the yy-axis and the class boundaries on the xx-axis.

Steps for drawing the ogive graph:

1 Complete a cumulative frequency column (by adding each frequency to the sum of all the frequencies before it in the table).
2 Expand the table to include coordinate points from the table values.
  • xx-intercept: (first class lower boundary; 00)
  • points after that: (class upper boundary; cumulative frequency)
3 Label your axes (the class boundaries on the xx-axis and cumulative frequency on the yy-axis).
4 Connect the points in order from left to right to make a smooth SS-shaped curve.
5 Check that the graph starts at the lower boundary of the first class (where the cumulative frequency is zero) and ends at the upper boundary of the last class (where the cumulative frequency is equal to the sample size).

The word cumulative means 'growing by adding one after the other'. The cumulative frequency of a class is the frequency for that class added to the frequency of all the previous classes. So, the cumulative frequency of the last class is equal to the whole sample size.

Group data is listed with non-overlapping interval classes such as a≤n<ba≤n<b (meaning nn is from aa up to but not including bb) or a<n≤ba<n≤b (meaning nn is from more than aa up to and including bb). The aa in these expressions represents the lower class boundary (telling you about the smallest value in the class) and the bb represents the upper class boundary (telling you about the biggest value in the class).

An ogive is an SS-shaped cumulative frequency graph. It is a line graph formed by plotting the cumulative frequency on the yy-axis and the class boundaries on the xx-axis.

Comparing histograms and their ogives

The figure below shows a histogram and an ogive. These two graphs represent the same data set.

  1. The histogram has a peak in the fifth interval and the bars after that peak get smaller. But the ogive continues to go up. Why does this happen?

    A The graphs do not follow the same scale.
    B The graphs are not using the same intervals.
    C The histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency.
    D The ogive is based on the midpoints of the intervals.
    Answer: The correct explanation is .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    How are the histogram and the ogive related to each other?

    STEP: Identify how histograms and ogives are related
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    This question is about how histograms and ogives are related to each other.

    • Histograms show the frequency for each interval (how many data values are in each interval). Each interval is separate from the others.
    • Ogives show the cumulative frequency for each interval. That means we add the frequencies of the intervals together as we go along.

    So the histogram shows the number of data values in each interval, and each interval is separate. But the ogive keeps adding those values up in a running total. As a result, the ogive keeps rising.

    NOTE: This is also why the ogive rises more quickly than the histogram on the left side of the histogram's peak.

    The correct statement is that the histogram shows frequencies but the ogive shows cumulative frequency, which is choice C.

    [−1 point ⇒ 2 / 3 points left]

    This question is about finding information on ogives. In this case, both questions focus on a particular point in time: 2525 seconds. This corresponds to the point circled below:

    For the first question we need to determine the number of students who burped before 2525 seconds. In other words, what is the total number of students who burped from when they finished the fizzy drink until 2525 seconds had passed.

    The point circled above has a time value of 2525 seconds (on the xx-axis). The yy-axis shows cumulative frequency, so we can find the total number of students who burped by that time on the yy-axis.

    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 3 points left]

    There were 2020 students who avoided burping for at least 2525 seconds.

The frequencies show how many data values are in each interval. But the cumulative frequency adds up the data values from the beginning to the end. In other words, the cumulative frequency is the running total of data values from the first interval to the last interval.

The cumulative frequency at a certain interval is the sum of the frequencies up to and including that interval. For example, to find the fourth cumulative frequency value we add up the first four frequencies:

7+0+3+2=127+0+3+2=12
NOTE: The second frequency is zero. And that is why the first and the second cumulative frequency values are equal.

Matching histograms and ogives

The histogram below shows test results for a class of 2626 students for a test with 1010 questions.

The data above can also be represented by an ogive. One of the ogives below is the correct ogive for the data. Which ogive is correct?

Answer: The correct ogive is .
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

Use the shape of the histogram to determine the answer. Remember that tall bars lead to big jumps on an ogive. Similarly, if the histogram does not have any tall peaks then the ogive should have no big jumps.

STEP: Use the shape of the histogram
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

In this question we must figure out how the shape of the histogram translates onto an ogive. Here are some key facts linking histograms and ogives:

  • Tall bars on the histogram correspond to steep sections on an ogive. This is because the tall bars indicate intervals which have a lot of data values.
  • Short bars on the histogram correspond to gentle gradients on an ogive. This is because the short bars indicate intervals which contain few data values.
  • Any interval on the histogram with no bar corresponds to a flat section on an ogive. This is because such an interval contains no data values, so the ogive cannot increase.

The figure below shows how the height of the bars creates the correct ogive.

The histogram in this question has a peak on the right side, in the seventh interval. At the same time, most of the bars on the left side are relatively small. So the corresponding ogive should increase quickly on the right side with the biggest jump in the seventh interval. On the left side it should increase very slowly because the histogram bars there are short.

The correct ogive must be graph A.

    STEP: Find the midpoints of the intervals
    [−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

    To estimate the mean (average) value of grouped data, we use the midpoints of the intervals. We do this because we do not know the individual data values - we only know how many data values are in each interval. We use the midpoints because they are the most reasonable assumption for the values of those data values. The midpoint values are:

    2,000≤m<2,400→2,2002,400≤m<2,800→2,6002,800≤m<3,200→3,0003,200≤m<3,600→3,4003,600≤m<4,000→3,8004,000≤m<4,400→4,2004,400≤m<4,800→4,6004,800≤m<5,200→5,0002,000≤m<2,400→2,2002,400≤m<2,800→2,6002,800≤m<3,200→3,0003,200≤m<3,600→3,4003,600≤m<4,000→3,8004,000≤m<4,400→4,2004,400≤m<4,800→4,6004,800≤m<5,200→5,000
    STEP: Compute the estimated mean of the data
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]
